Disk Forensics > [T6]: Shellbags: Investigating User Folder Activity

(3) Shellbags

Shellbags are two registry sub-keys ("BagMRU" and "Bags") that store details about folders the user viewed using file explorer, such as window size, position, icons, and view options set by the user. Shell bags registry keys are stored in two hives:

  1. C:\Users\<user>\NTUSER.dat
  2. C:\Users\<user>\AppData\Local\Microsoft\Windows\USRCLASS.dat

The "BagMRU" key stores folder names/paths, and the "Bags" key stores window location, size, and view mode. These keys exist in the following places.

  • NTUSER.DAT\Software\Microsoft\Windows\Shell\
  • NTUSER.DAT\Software\Microsoft\Windows\ShellNoRoam\
  • USRCLASS.DAT\Local Settings\Software\Microsoft\Windows\Shell\
  • USRCLASS.DAT\Local Settings\Software\Microsoft\Windows\ShellNoRoam\

But how can this be helpful in an investigation? Shellbags represent a log of all folders a user viewed on a system, including external drives (even if they are not connected anymore). An attacker can download some tools to the victim's computer and securely delete them later. Using shellbags, you can determine what folders any user viewed and what the content of each folder was -even if it does not exist anymore.

Parsing shellbags is a tedious task. Thanks to Eric, "ShellbagsExplorer." It can automatically parse it and present it in a nice view.

Parsed shellbags - (zoom in).

  1. File explorer-like view of Shellbags.
  2. The content of the selected directory. In our case, the content of the "HR" directory. Note that all folders under "HR" have been deleted from the system, yet, Shellbags still holds this information.
  3. More details about the selected object.
